“Agarbatti” is slow burning incense sticks which develop an odour that has religious and spiritual significance. They have a practical function as well, as they help create cool air when placed on a fan. According to butterworth, this astonishing invention is welcome in British cities but not in Germany, where some clever sausage aficionados have given their name for the product.

Air conditioners are increasingly common in richer parts of the world, but the gadget is banned in most of German cities because of the association people have between air pollution and the cooling system, according to carl duffield, a journalist at GermanNewspapers.com.

“It is considered the quintessence of decadent luxury,” he said. “Somewhere spring-summer has bled into autumn-winter, so living comfort with heavily air conditioned apartments has become the norm, even though this is not the worst day of the year or anything near it.”
